In Scotland, an employee who has recently experienced the death of a child may be eligible for parental bereavement leave under the Parental Bereavement Leave Regulations 2020. To determine entitlement, the employee must satisfy one of the conditions specified in paragraph (2) of regulation 4.

The conditions include:

(a) The employee is C's parent;
(b) The employee is C's natural parent and named in an order made pursuant to section 51A(2)(a) of the Adoption and Children Act 2002 or section 11(3)(aa) of the Children (Scotland) Act 1995, provided that such an order has not subsequently been revoked or discharged;
(c) The employee is a person with whom C has been placed for adoption, for so long as that placement has not been disrupted;
(d) The employee is an adopter who has received official notification in respect of C;
(e) The employee is an intended parent of C;
(f) The employee is C's parent in fact; or
(g) The employee is the partner of P.

It is essential to note that the employee must also comply with the notice requirements in regulation 6. 

Once the employee satisfies one of these conditions, they are entitled to take parental bereavement leave under this regulation. The regulations provide for a certain period of leave, which can be taken without penalty or deduction from pay.

The employer has an obligation to provide the necessary support and resources during this time. However, the specifics of the obligations vary depending on the individual circumstances.

In general, the employer is required to ensure that the employee's job is protected during the bereavement leave period. This may involve offering alternative arrangements or ensuring that the employee's pay remains intact.

However, it's worth noting that the regulations do not explicitly state what obligations the employer has in terms of providing additional support or resources during this time.

It is recommended that employees review their employment contract and speak with HR or a supervisor to understand their specific entitlements and any additional support they may be eligible for.

